<TEXT>
the parents of an infant girl who starved to 
death on an herbal diet were sentenced to nearly two years in 
prison on tuesday for failing to provide the necessities of life 
for their daughter 
khachadour atikian 54 and his wife sonia 38 showed little 
emotion as they were led handcuffed from ontario supreme court 
after justice john odriscoll imposed the maximum sentence two 
years less one day in jail 
their 16monthold daughter lorie died in september 1987 her 
emaciated jaundiced body had wasted away to 11 pounds 
the judge said the maximum term is reserved for the worst 
scenarios adding quite frankly i cant think of a worse 
possible situation than this 
how could anyone in their right mind and in their right senses 
not see this helpless child id call not one but a dozen 
ambulances odriscoll said 
the couple came to canada from lebanon in the mid1970s and have 
two healthy teenage children 
a jury convicted them this month after witnesses at the sixweek 
trial testified about the atikians involvement with an herbalist 
evidence suggested the herbalist persuaded the parents that 
doctors would kill their baby 
one witness said the herbalist told the mother taking the infant 
to a doctor would be like holding a loaded gun to the babys head 
and pulling the trigger 
testimony said the herbalist insisted the atikians should follow 
his health and diet regimen if they wanted to have the 
superbaby they planned 
a picture of lorie on her first birthday presented as evidence 
showed a normal healthy child a police photograph taken hours 
after lories death showed her birdlike frame covered with rashes 
and open sores 
the jury was told lorie had not been seen by a doctor for more 
than eight months and had never been immunized against disease her 
diet consisted of brown rice raw vegetables pureed fruits and 
fruit juices but no milk 
the day before the baby died the herbalist told mrs atikian to 
wrap lorie in cabbage leaves to draw out the poisons the jury was 
told 
the herbalist is being investigated by the ontario college of 
physicians and surgeons to see if he has been practicing medicine 
without a license such a finding could lead to criminal charges 
</TEXT>
