<TEXT>
catching a genetically engineered cold 
might one day be a way to alleviate some of the worst symptoms of 
cystic fibrosis researchers say 
researchers are trying to insert a lifesaving gene into viruses 
that cause the common cold such genetically engineered viruses 
might be able to carry the gene into the lung tissue of cystic 
fibrosis patients whose lungs are clogged with mucus and prone to 
sometimes fatal infections 
these are already being tested said robert beall vice 
president for medical affairs at the cystic fibrosis foundation in 
bethesda md 
the genetically altered cold viruses are among cystic fibrosis 
research studies made possible by last years discovery of the 
cystic fibrosis gene 
on monday lap chee tsui one of the discoverers of the gene 
said that a single rare kind of defect in the gene has been found 
in about 70 percent of cystic fibrosis carriers he spoke at the 
jackson laboratory in bar harbor 
cystic fibrosis is the most common genetic disease in 
caucasians it affects about one in 2000 caucasian babies but it 
is relatively uncommon in other populations 
the rare defect found in many carriers occurs almost exclusively 
in caucasians explaining why the disease is more common in 
caucasians than in others said tsui professor of molecular and 
medical genetics at the university of toronto 
it is marked by digestive and respiratory problems especially 
the buildup of thick mucus in the lungs that can lead to recurrent 
infections that often prove fatal 
the cause of the disease is not known but the discovery of the 
faulty gene should allow researchers to sort out exactly what is 
going wrong in the lungs pancreas and other affected organs 
for example researchers have now identified an antibody to 
track the protein made by the cystic fibrosis gene beall said 
studies suggest that the protein is getting where it is supposed to 
go but it is not doing the job it is supposed to do 
such clues are essential in figuring out precisely what is going 
wrong in cystic fibrosis patients then devising ways to fix it 
one unfortunate development has been the discovery that in 
addition to the one defect identified in caucasians more than 40 
other kinds of mutations in the cystic fibrosis gene can also cause 
cystic fibrosis 
that complicates the job of prenatal diagnosis of cystic 
fibrosis at present researchers cannot tell parents whether their 
children will be born with the disease 
in families in which one child has the disease however doctors 
can do prenatal tests to determine whether subsequent fetuses are 
affected with the disease 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

