gasoline is the dirtiest in seattle and the 
cleanest in miami as far as levels of cancercausing benzene are 
concerned according to a survey by a consumer group 
the survey released monday by citizens action revealed widely 
different levels of toxic aromatics especially benzene in 
gasoline depending on regions of the country 
benzene and other aromatic additives are used to boost gasoline 
octane but they are highly toxic and are of concern to health 
specialists because of motorists exposure to vapors during 
refueling 
the study found that premium gasoline sold in the west generally 
contained higher levels of aromatics including benzene an 
exception appeared to be atlanta where the level of benzene in 
premium gasoline 29 percent was second only to seattle 3 
percent both los angeles and san francisco had benzene levels of 
27 percent on average 
the american petroleum institute representing major oil 
companies said benzene content in gasoline nationwide averaged 16 
percent for regular and 17 percent for premium grades nationwide 
clean air legislation in the final stages of being approved by 
congress calls for refiners to limit their benzene levels to less 
than 1 percent 
shell premium gasoline sold in atlanta had the highest content 
of benzene of any gasoline tested 54 percent exxons premium in 
los angeles and chevrons premium in san francisco all contained 
more than 36 percent benzene 
this is gasoline at its dirtiest said edwin rothschild 
energy policy director for citizen action 
taking into account all 18 cities surveyed chevron had the 
highest average level of benzene 28 percent for premium and 2 
percent for regular 
the api responding to the survey accused citizen action of 
misusing data to present an unduly alarmist picture of the 
health risks to motorists the trade group said exposure levels 
to consumers are too low to pose a danger 
the environmental protection agency has estimated that the 
cancer risk from routine refueling over a lifetime may be eight 
additional cancers per 100000 people exposed the risk is higher 
for those working at service stations or living near them or near 
gasoline refineries the agency said 
api spokesman earl ross called the regional variations not 
unusual gasolines are blended differently for different parts of 
the country he said because of differences in driving 
conditions climate altitude and seasonal changes 
the survey by citizen action a washingtonbased consumer and 
environmental group was based on gasoline samples tested in 18 
cities by the motor vehicle manufacturers association 
the survey found that some gasoline brands already meet the 
anticipated clean air requirement being considered by congress 
in miami where average benzene levels in premium gasoline were 
only 1 percent mobils premium had a benzene level of onehalf of 
1 percent and three other brands union amoco and exxon all 
