<TEXT>
the man chosen by president bush to be the 
next supreme court justice is being described as a cautious 
conservative an agile thinker and a judge hardly known outside his 
home state of new hampshire 
david h souter who would be the nations 105th justice if 
confirmed by the senate has an extensive record as a state judge 
that reveals little inclination toward sweeping pronouncements or 
rulings 
it would be very surprising if he turned out to be anything 
but a conservative likely to be allied on the high court with 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justices antonin scalia and 
anthony m kennedy said university of virginia law professor ae 
dick howard 
preliminary assessments of souters judicial philosophy were 
based less on his writings and rulings than on who his friends and 
political allies are 
souter was a state trial judge for five years before he was 
appointed to the new hampshire supreme court in 1983 by thengov 
john sununu sununu now is bushs chief of staff and considered by 
many to be the leading white house advocate for conservative causes 
souter also has the enthusiastic support of sen warren rudman 
a moderate new hampshire republican 
rudman who as state attorney general years ago hired souter 
once said his protege possesses the most brilliant legal mind 
he had ever encountered 
bush repeatedly said monday he picked souter without examining 
the nominees position on abortion and there is barely a clue as 
to how souter might rule on the issue 
in a 1986 case before the new hampshire supreme court souter 
joined the majority in ruling that doctors have a responsibility to 
test for birth defects and inform pregnant women of the option of 
abortion 
we recognize that the termination of pregnancy involves 
controversial and divisive social issues said the opinion 
nonetheless the supreme court of the united states has held that 
a woman has a constitutionally secured right to terminate a 
pregnancy 
in a concurring opinion souter questioned the impact the 
decision would have on doctors who oppose abortion on moral 
grounds he said such physicians should not have to choose 
between rendering services that they morally condemn and leaving 
their profession in order to escape malpractice exposures 
conservatives and republicans say they are reluctant to jump to 
conclusions without further examination of souters record 
nan aron of the liberal alliance for justice said that based on 
her preliminary soundings souter can be characterized as a 
moderate conservative 
john scully of the conservative washington legal foundation said 
were not celebrating but are optimistic that conservatives 
will be able to rally behind souter 
souter went through senate confirmation hearings when bush named 
him to the 1st us circuit court of appeals earlier this year but 
his experience on the federal bench is so limited that his 
biography is not included in the official directory of federal 
judges 
he is more familiar to legal observers back home 
he does not pay any attention to the emotional political 
aspects of cases before him said stanley m brown a 
manchester nh lawyer and a former american bar association 
officer he doesnt go out blazing new pathways thats not his 
forte 
in an interview published in may in massachusetts lawyers 
weekly souter said he doesnt like being described as a strict 
constructionist 
on constitutional matters i am of the interpretivist 
school he said were not looking for the original 
application were looking for meaning here thats a very 
different thing 
souter was the lone dissenter in a 1985 state supreme court 
decision that struck down the use of police sobriety checkpoints 
the nations highest court upheld such police tactics earlier this 
year 
he also was part of a 32 majority when the state supreme court 
in 1986 allowed the main owner of the seabrook nuclear plant to 
sell bonds needed to complete the longentangled project the court 
rejected appeals by state consumer advocates and environmentalists 
in one of the rare civil rights cases in which souter 
participated he joined the state supreme courts ruling in 1987 
that said homosexuals may be barred from becoming adoptive or 
foster parents but the state court said in that decision that 
homosexuals may not be barred from running day care centers 
people for the american way a liberal group said its review of 
souters state supreme court record indicates he interprets 
constitutional guarantees narrowly especially in criminal cases 
the organization criticized souter for an opinion that 
overturned a sexual assault conviction souter held that the 
defendant should have been allowed to present testimony that the 
victim behaved in a sexually provocative manner toward several men 
in a tavern the group said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

