<TEXT>
david h souter shook hands with president 
bush on monday afternoon for the first time then sat down in the 
white house family quarters for a 45minute chat 
a few hours later bush was introducing souter as his nominee to 
be the next us supreme court justice less than 72 hours after 
william j brennan stepped down from the court 
although his nomination unfolded with surprising speed 
administration officials said that theyve had an eye on souter for 
some time 
shortly after he took office bush asked the justice department 
and white house staff to put together a list of potential supreme 
court nominees souters name was placed on that list early last 
year 
he was bought to the attention of justice department judicial 
candidate screeners by white house chief of staff john sununu said 
a senior administration official as governor of new hampshire 
sununu had appointed souter to that states highest court 
souters name came up again last fall when officials were 
searching for someone to fill a vacancy on the 1st circuit court of 
appeals in boston he underwent a series of interviews last year 
and bush nominated him to that court on jan 24 
after the american bar association gave him its highest rating 
well qualified the senate confirmed souter on april 27 he 
joined the 1st circuit only in may and hasnt had the opportunity 
to publish any rulings 
souters name came up again saturday morning when bush attorney 
general dick thornburgh sununu and white house counsel boyden gray 
met to launch their weekend search for new justice said another 
senior official 
we know this man because we had this man through our judicial 
process last fall said the official who spoke on condition of 
anonymity 
at saturdays meeting bush was given background materials on a 
dozen or so potential candidates to study over the weekend 
officials said the president added several names for 
consideration which were given a cursory check by those 
assigned to review the candidates the official said 
white house and justice department officials met throughout the 
weekend 
no short list was drawn up but on monday bush arranged to 
conduct two interviews one with souter and another with a 
candidate whom administration officials declined to identify 
the president talked with souter in the family quarters of the 
white house and later filled three legalsized pages with his 
handwritten feelings or conclusions about the candidate said 
spokesman marlin fitzwater 
while souter waited elsewhere in the white house bush weighed 
the strengths and weaknesses of souter and two other 
candidates then wrote out three more pages before making up his 
mind fitzwater said 
after a twohour wait souter was called to the oval office 
where bush offered him the nomination 
