preliminary results from sundays primary indicated that just 96 
of 300 candidates from the five opposition parties survived prime 
minister sharavyn gunjaadorg said 
the balloting was to reduce the field of 2400 candidates to 
860 two for each seat in the national legislature or great 
peoples hural the final round of voting is sunday 
gunjaadorg maintained that a communist victory would not hinder 
mongolias dramatic transformation which began in december from 
an authoritarian oneparty state obedient to moscow to a 
multiparty nation eager for western contact and investment 
he said the noncommunist parties would still have some 
possibility to get into power 
the oppositions only hope for gaining a significant voice in 
government lies in the 53seat small hural which will handle 
legislation between annual sessions of the great hural 
its seats will be assigned to the various parties according to 
the percentage of the vote each receives 
even a communistcontrolled great hural would be very different 
from its predecessor however because most of the partys 
candidates this time are intellectuals and bureacrats rather than 
herders and workers as in the past 
the election process so far is a comparatively free and fair 
