<TEXT>
in some areas of cuba oxen are replacing 
gasguzzling tractors in havana office workers are being asked 
now and then to do without airconditioning fuel at most state 
enterprises has been cut back 10 percent 
and this could be only the beginning 
cubans are bracing for tough times the result in part of last 
years democratic upheaval in eastern europe and the prospect that 
cuba may no longer be able to count on soviet generosity to 
buttress its economy 
for years cuba has suffered from a us trade and financial 
embargo 
but now all over the island cubans are being warned at town 
meetings that additional belt tightening may be around the corner 
if bargainrate soviet oil supplies averaging about 90 million 
barrels annually are cut off and there is no money to tap 
alternate sources 
soviet deliveries already have slowed and president fidel 
castro alluded to the problem in a speech last month 
stubborn realities are there we constantly have to think in 
terms of less and less fuel we have to tell the truth 
an added concern is that soviet officials have spoken publicly 
about the possibility of a phased reduction of overall soviet 
economic assistance to cuba a windfall estimated by some at 4 
billion to 5 billion a year 
us sources have said there has been a marked decline in 
purchases of cuban sugar by the soviet union at prices 
substantially higher than world market levels a form of subsidy 
for the cuban economy 
president bush has been appealing to the soviets to cut castro 
off the united states has expressed reluctance to provide direct 
aid to the troubled soviet economy as long as moscow sends billions 
of rubles to cuba 
special period in peacetime is the somewhat benign sounding 
name for the draconian measures castro has in mind in the event 
cuba has to go it alone 
to show that he means business dress rehearsals are being held 
around the island to give cubans a taste of what may lie ahead 
oxen are being tried out on farms in western cuba 
military recruits are being asked to extend their tours of duty 
by two months to help the armed services become selfsufficient in 
food 
under the most extreme austerity measures thousands could be 
thrown out of work in havana partly because a suspension of most 
bus service would make it impossible for many to commute 
already some offices are experimenting with allowing employees 
to try working at home to see whether their labors would still be 
useful 
under the worst case scenario castro has said that all housing 
construction would be halted immediately and the manufacture of 
adult clothing would be suspended 
not all enterprises would be affected cubas ambitious tourism 
program slated to bring an almost fivefold increase in the number 
of foreign visitors to 15 million by 1995 would be spared 
castro is discovering somewhat belatedly what his noncommunist 
predecessors here knew all along as earners of foreign exchange 
cubas biggest assets are its tropical climate and its miles of 
sandy beaches 
some cuban officials believe that a shift in trading partners 
from the former socialist bloc to western industrialized nations 
will brighten cubas economic prospects over the long run 
castro has complained bitterly about the low quality products 
sent by eastern european countries to cuba in exchange for prized 
cuban exports such as sugar citrus fruit and nickel 
cuba may now be able to use these exports to buy high quality 
goods from the capitalist west the officials said but reshaping 
foreign trade relationships takes time and for now the future is 
extraordinarily bleak 
some cubans have lost hope 
more than two dozen presumed asylum seekers are holed up at 
three european embassies these days they decided to abandon the 
revolution even though castro has said none of them will be given 
permission to leave the country 
according to the us coast guard the number of cubans who fled 
to florida during the first six months of this year totals 196 
compared with 57 for the same period last year 
but castro seems determined to maintain his orthodox brand of 
marxism even at the cost of the most farreaching austerity 
measures he has criticized gorbachevs reforms and condemned the 
changes in eastern europe 
if in five years we dont build housing if thats the price 
for saving the revolution then we will spend five years without 
building them he says 
