<TEXT>
five months after it was suspended because of an 
explosion europes ariane program is back in business with todays 
launch of a rocket carrying a double payload of french and german 
television satellites 
the 37th ariane rocket was to blast off tonight from the ariane 
facility in french guiana south america with a 49minute launch 
window beginning at 625 pm est 
it is the first attempt at an ariane launch since a similar 
rocket carrying two japanese communications satellites blew up less 
than two minutes after takeoff on feb 22 both satellites were 
destroyed 
investigators said the explosion was caused by a tiny piece of 
cloth that clogged a line carrying water coolant to one of the 
engines 
the respected french weekly lexpress reported in a cover story 
that the explosion and at least two previous ariane failures may 
have been caused by sabotage 
officials of arianespace the commercial branch of the european 
space agency have said there was no evidence to indicate sabotage 
but that technical and security checks would be intensified 
the ariane project has been dogged by embarrassing and costly 
setbacks including rockets that have exploded or crashed and 
expensive delays 
but ariane rockets dominate the private aerospace industry 
carrying about half of the worlds commercial payloads into space 
excluding todays flight arianespace has contracts worth 28 
billion to launch 37 more satellites 
ariane rockets have sent into space 45 commercial satellites 
from canada france west germany great britain india italy 
spain and the united states as well as international organizations 
such as intelsat and eutelsat 
ariane is facing increased competition however from american 
privatesector rockets including the titan4 made by martin 
marietta corp general dynamics atlascentaur and the delta built 
by mcdonnell douglas 
until now us rockets have mainly launched military and 
scientific satellites under the supervision of the us air force 
and the national aeronautics and space administration 
china also is a contender in commercial launches with its long 
march rocket as well as the soviet union with its proton and japan 
with the h2 rocket now under development 
