the united states will begin removing 
its chemical weapons from west germany this week and will ship them 
a us atoll in the pacific where they will be destroyed in an 
incinerator officials said 
the west german defense ministry said monday in a statement that 
the operation to remove the 100000 artillery rounds will begin 
thursday 
a us army spokesman in west germany said he was awaiting 
confirmation from washington and could not confirm that date 
chancellor helmut kohl and former president reagan agreed in 
1986 to remove the weapons by 1992 president bush advanced the 
timetable to 1990 said james boyle a spokesman for headquarters 
us army europe 
boyle said the artillery shells in 6inchdiameter and 8inch 
sizes are loaded with liquid nerve agents 
he said they have been stored since 1968 at a us military site 
in clausen a small town near the us military complex at 
kaiserslautern in southwestern west germany 
this is the most wellplanned operation weve had here as far 
as the transport of munitions there is safety measure upon safety 
measure redundant throughout the operation boyle said 
each convoy will include 20 flatbed trucks loaded with the 
chemical weapons stored in two airtight steel containers and 60 
other escort trucks including german and us security forces 
emergency crews and decontamination teams he said 
boyle said there would be about 30 convoys running one a day 
the trucks will travel a variety of routes for safety and 
security reasons from clausen to a us depot at miesau about 30 
miles away he said 
the containers will be loaded onto special trains at miesau for 
the trip north to nordenham on the north sea where they will be 
reloaded onto us navy ships for transport to johnston atoll in 
the pacific 
boyle said the chemical weapons will be destroyed later in a 
specially built incinerator on the us atoll about 800 miles 
southwest of hawaii 
