<TEXT>
government troops have captured a key 
northern village in fierce fighting that left 30 tamil rebels dead 
military officials said today 
the village controls access to the jaffna peninsula where the 
rebels are based 
four soldiers were killed in the monday attack in which 
helicopters dropped troops and commandos behind rebel defenses to 
take the village of paranthan officials said they spoke on 
condition of anonymity 
paranthan is seven miles south of elephant pass a causeway that 
links the jaffna peninsula with the mainland 
the capture of paranthan could provide a launching pad for 
attacks on jaffna which the tamil tiger rebels have held since 
they repudiated a ceasefire with government forces on june 11 
the rebels control all of jaffna except for four government 
bases that have been under siege for more than a month almost one 
million civilians mostly ethnic tamils live on the peninsula 
tamil militants took up arms in 1983 claiming their community 
was being discriminated against in jobs education and language by 
the sinhalese majority 
tamils who are mostly hindus make up 18 percent of sri lankas 
16 million people sinhalese who are mostly buddhists comprise 75 
percent of the population and control the army and the government 
at least 13800 people have died in the tamil insurrection 
last week the rebels blew up the elephant pass causeway the 
only viable route for a largescale crossing into the peninsula 
military officials said the causeway has since been repaired 
at least 2890 combatants have been killed in fighting since the 
rebels violated the june ceasefire 
the latest casualties included eight soldiers killed monday near 
the east coast port of trincomalee in a rebel ambush military 
officials said 
another soldier was killed near batticaloa south of 
trincomalee they said 
when the fighting began last month the rebels held the 
tamildominated areas on the north and east of the island the army 
has dislodged the rebels from most towns in the east and the 
guerrillas have retreated into the jungles to fight what could be a 
protracted war 
in the north the army has been unable to make significant 
headway because of the difficult access to jaffna 
