<TEXT>
us supreme court nominee david souter 
issued a ruling on the new hampshire supreme court that could be 
seen as arguing that doctors should be free to decide whether to 
counsel women about abortions 
souter agreed with and issued a concurring opinion in a 1986 
case in which the court said it would not recognize a right not to 
be born 
the ruling dealt with a womans lawsuit against her doctor 
charging that he did not advise her of the possibility that the 
german measles she contracted during pregnancy would result in 
birth defects 
her daughter was born with multiple birth defects and she 
argued that she should have known of the possibility and been 
counseled about the possibility of abortion 
in a unanimous decision the court ruled that it had no business 
deciding whether such a child would be better off having been 
aborted but it did rule that the parents of children with birth 
defects have a right to sue 
it also held that doctors have a responsibility to test for 
birth defects and inform pregnant women of the possibility of 
defects to give them the option of abortion 
we recognize that the termination of pregnancy involves 
controversial and divisive social issues said the opinion with 
which souter agreed nonetheless the supreme court of the united 
states has held that a woman has a constitutionally secured right 
to terminate a pregnancy 
the mother linda smith also made her daughter heather a 
plaintiff but the court rejected the childs suit saying the 
right to life and the principle that all are equal under the law 
are basic to our constitutional order to presume to decide that 
heathers life is not worth living would be to forsake these 
ideals 
souter agreed with the ruling and raised an additional question 
