<TEXT>
ten leatherback turtles will be 
fitted with transmitters and tracked in international waters with 
the help of nasa satellites an official said 
fisheries department director general shahrom abdul majid said 
monday the project would provide accurate information on the 
movements of the giant leatherback turtles between their annual 
nestings in malaysia 
scientists say the species which has been around for an 
estimated 150 million years is facing extinction due to pollution 
and pilfering of their eggs which are a delicacy in malaysia 
the turtles measure up to 5 feet in diameter can weigh 900 lbs 
and live for about 100 years 
majid said malaysia will be the third country after french 
guiana and the united states to use this system the national news 
agency bernama reported 
he was speaking after launching the project at rantau abang the 
site of the turtles annual nesting migration 
the program involves using nasa satellites to relay signals 
emitted by a platform transmitter terminal on the back of each 
turtle to ground stations the project cost 27000 
the turtles roam the seas around japan the philippines and 
australia but return annually to rantau abang 180 miles northeast 
of the capital of kuala lumpur between june to august to lay their 
eggs 
in the 1950s between 1700 and 2000 of the turtles came ashore 
annually but their numbers dwindled to about 500 per year during 
the past few years and to only about 60 last year government 
officials said 
</TEXT>
