<TEXT>
a ruling that a countys voting districts 
should be redrawn to increase black voting strength was overturned 
by a federal appeals court panel tuesday because the lawsuit was 
filed too late 
the ruling was a setback for the american civil liberties union 
which has sought redistricting to increase black voter strength in 
about 18 virginia localities 
the plaintiffs black voters in brunswick county in southern 
virginia probably will appeal their lawyer said were 
incredibly disappointed and we think the decision was very 
inappropriate said the attorney gerald t zerkin 
the ruling by a threejudge panel of the 4th us circuit court 
of appeals overturned an order by us district judge james r 
spencer that the countys voting districts be redrawn 
the plaintiffs delay in challenging a 1971 redistricting was 
inexcusable and unreasonable said the opinion by judge robert f 
chapman 
the appellate panel also said it would make no sense to change 
the countys voting districts just before 1990 census figures 
become available 
a courtordered reapportionment at this date would be 
completely gratuitous because there are no elections scheduled 
before november 1991 and the 1990 census figures may require 
reapportionment chapman said in the ruling joined by judges 
james m sprouse and william w wilkins jr 
if the plaintiffs believe the 1991 redistricting violates the 
us voting rights act they can file another lawsuit the judges 
said 
until tuesdays ruling the aclu has won outofcourt 
settlements or court rulings that were not appealed in nearly all 
the redistricting cases it pursued in virginia said kent willis 
director of the state aclu chapter a case against henrico county 
is pending before the 4th circuit 
brunswick county which is 57 percent black has a fivemember 
board of supervisors elected from singlemember districts four of 
the districts have populations that are more than half black but 
only two have elected black supervisors 
the board created the districts after the 1970 census and left 
them intact after the 1980 census 
the plaintiffs voiced no objection either to the 1971 
redistricting or to the 1981 decision not to redistrict and waited 
until september 1988 to file this action the appeals panel said 
the judges rejected the plaintiffs contention that the delay 
gave them information from several elections on which to base their 
claim that blacks are discriminated against in the county 
the plaintiffs in the exercise of reasonable diligence could 
have discovered at a much earlier time the facts upon which they 
now base their claim the opinion said 
zerkin protested we relied on the analysis of voting records 
that included elections in 1987 if we had brought it earlier the 
first thing they would have said is you have insufficent data 
zerkin also said the rural county has gained so few people that 
the 1990 redistricting is unlikely to produce major changes 
the net effect of this decision is that we have to start all 
over again he said 
raymond s daniel vice chairman of the brunswick county board 
of supervisors said he was pleased the ruling was in favor of 
brunswick county daniel said he had not seen the ruling and did 
not want to comment further 
