editors note this report is based in part on a pool dispatch 
filed by journalists in monrovia including ap correspondent 
michael goldsmith 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
soldiers loyal to the president fought 
off rebels and appeared in control of the city tuesday after an 
ambush on the capital insurgents launched another attack from the 
sea 
a spokesman for president samuel doe said the seaborne attack 
appeared to have been launched by a us submarine the state 
department denied the allegation 
a presidential spokesman selly thompson also told the british 
broadcasting corp in london that government troops were advancing 
against rebels in monrovia 
followers of rebel leader prince johnson penetrated the city 
center monday after wading through swampland and evading troops 
guarding bridges into town followers of charles taylor a rival 
rebel commander were blocked by government troops in the citys 
eastern suburbs taylor said he had infiltrated some men into the 
capital but only in small numbers 
taylor and johnson split sometime in the past three months and 
some foreign diplomats have said johnsons group is now stronger 
than taylors 
witnesses said an unidentified vessel approached the coastline 
in the darkness and fired at least six rounds at does mansion doe 
was believed to be inside the compound 
troops inside returned fire and the booming of cannon shots 
echoed through the city after the boat sped away one shot from 
the mansion was seen to fall harmlessly into the sea a few hundred 
yards offshore 
the damage to the heavily fortified mansion could not be 
immediately determined reporters who tried to go there or to the 
nearby ministry of information were turned back by soldiers 
later thompson read a statement to the bbc saying the mansion 
had been the target of a missile attack from the sea by what seemed 
to be a united states submarine 
the african nation founded by freed american slaves 150 years 
ago has traditionally had close ties with washington but 
washington has refused to send in a peacekeeping force and on 
saturday doe ordered the american military attache expelled 
accusing him of helping the rebels 
the united states denied the accusations it has offered to 
provide safe conduct out of the country for doe 
in washington the state department flatly denied it had fired 
on does compound 
it was not known how many soldiers were still fighting on the 
government side other than the 500 members of does presidential 
guard some government forces remained in pockets outside the 
capital but were unable to offer much help against the rebels who 
have advanced steadily since launching their siege in december 
government forces between taylors men and the capital included 
the 72nd infantry battalion and units based at schiefflin army 
base the infantry battalion was said to be putting up stiff 
resistance units at the army base had ventured out on several 
occasions to retake ground held by rebels according to reports 
from the rebel side 
troops loyal to doe patrolled monrovias streets shops were 
closed civilians searching in vain for food were harassed by 
soldiers nervous after the surprise attack monday by followers of 
prince johnson 
little is known about johnson he apparently served in the 
liberian armed forces and was a supporter of brig gen thomas 
quiwonkpa who launched a 1985 coup attempt against doe johnson 
joined up with taylor last year and was a lieutenant in the rebel 
national patriotic liberation front 
hes posing a much more formidable challenge than we 
thought one us official said of johnson 
there have been conflicting reports on whether johnson and 
taylor have reconciled 
the rebels have accused doe who took power of the nation of 24 
million people in a 1980 coup of corruption mismanagement and 
human rights abuses at least nine male bodies most of them 
stripped were found on a beach not far from the citys embassy 
district tuesday other bodies were scattered nearby witnesses 
told a photographer that soldiers had brought the people there 
during the night and summarily executed them 
does troops fearful the rebels will kill former soldiers if 
they take the capital have frequently been seen shooting 
civilians the civilians usually belong to the gio or mano tribes 
which provide the main support for taylor 
taylors soldiers have similarly executed troops belonging to 
does krahn tribe 
doe has been deserted by nearly all senior members of his 
government but had not asked the united states for help a us 
official in washington said monday 
doe has said he will not leave the besieged capital until the 
civil war has been decided sources said his presidential guard 
would not let him leave unless they were provided safe passage to 
their home territory in grand gedeh county 
