<TEXT>
animal rights activists are gathering 
on chincoteague island this week to protest what they call the 
mistreatment of the islands famed wild ponies during the annual 
pony swim 
every year for 65 years the volunteer firemen of chincoteague 
have rounded up the wild ponies on the neighboring coastal barrier 
island of assateague and auctioned off some of the foals to control 
the size of the herd 
on wednesday the ponies will be driven across the narrow inlet 
that separates the islands and herded through the towns streets to 
a penning area this years auction will be thursday with the 
proceeds going to the volunteer fire department 
last year the department sold 77 foals for 40000 some of the 
foals purchased are returned to the island at the request of the 
buyers 
the weeklong celebration brings about 30000 people to the tiny 
community 
the animals are thought to be the descendants of ponies that 
washed ashore from shipwrecks during colonial times they gained 
fame from marguerite henrys childrens classic misty of 
chincoteague first published in 1947 
animal rights groups such as the charlottesvillebased voices 
for animals and people for the ethical treatment of animals in 
washington dc say the round up penning and auction are cruel 
especially to the young animals 
the ponies must swim unfamiliar waters after which they are 
stampeded through town separated from their mothers and sold at 
auction said susan weidman of voices for animals 
its obvious that the fire company does not have the best 
interest of the horses at heart she said 
peta is upset that unweaned foals are auctioned off such 
animals need special care if they are to survive away from their 
mother said peta spokeswoman siriol evans 
none of the groups said they planned to actively protest the 
pony swim or auction this year but will observe the events and 
help the animals if necessary 
the humane society of the united states has been monitoring the 
event for 20 years 
gail eisnitz a field investigator for the humane society in 
washington said conditions for the animals have improved although 
six animals have died in the last two years 
one year horses ate toxic chokecherry leaves off bushes 
overhanging the pen became sick and died 
as a result of those deaths the chincoteague national wildlife 
refuge on assateague threatened to revoke the fire departments 
permit to graze the animals on the refuge if the department did not 
provide a veterinarian for the swim penning and auction 
last year the department had veterinarians on call but two 
horses still died 
this year terry said the fire department has hired a 
veterinarian to stay on the site full time 
ms eisnitz said the national fish and wildlife service has 
demanded other improvements in exchange for the grazing rights 
the fire department has enlarged the corral provided a shaded 
area and more water for the animals they have also cut back the 
chokecherry bushes she said 
the fire department works year round to help the herd which 
numbers around 200 the animals are regularly checked by a 
veterinarian 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

