<TEXT>
boy scout and girl scout movements are making a 
strong comeback in eastern europe after decades of communist 
repression the world organization of the scout movement said 
tuesday after readmitting hungary and czechoslovakia 
scouting officials attending the 32nd world conference of 
scouting also received encouraging news about the prospects for the 
movements revival in the soviet union where communistcontrolled 
youth leagues replaced the prerevolutionary scouting groups 
in a letter read at the conference tuesday soviet president 
mikhail s gorbachev praised the noble objectives of the 
scouting movement 
he also thanked the world organization for helping 1235 youths 
from the region around the stricken chernobyl nuclear power plant 
spend summer vacations in western europe 
gorbachevs letter was read by albert lichanov president of the 
soviet childrens fund he said the soviet union no longer sought 
to prevent the formation of independent youth organizations 
more and more scouting movements exist he said 
jacques moreillon secretary general of the world organization 
said the soviets had given a green light for the rebirth of 
scouting in the ussr 
scoutings status in eastern europe was a major topic during the 
first full day of the weeklong conference which has brought 
together about 1000 officials of national scouting organizations 
in more than 100 countries 
in the past two years there has been a spectacular renewal of 
scouting in eastern europe a spontaneous intense movement 
the world organization said in a memorandum distributed at the 
conference 
the conference opened monday night with a welcoming message from 
president francois mitterrand 
mitterrand saluted the scouting movements universality and 
said its renaissance in eastern europe shows that scouting 
doesnt exist without democracy 
hungary and czechoslovakia were among several countries accepted 
this week as members of the world organization others include 
guinea comoros and newly independent namibia 
hungary and czechoslovakia had scouting programs until the 
1950s when they were suppressed by communist authorities the 
programs survived clandestinely with occasional brief periods of 
legalization until restrictions were lifted in 1988 
hungary now has about 10000 scouts and czechoslovakia more 
than 70000 according to the world scout bureau it also 
summarized the past and present status of scouting elsewhere in 
eastern europe 
the soviet union there were nearly 100000 scouts prior to 
1917 but the movement was suppressed after the bolshevik 
revolution now scouting has revived in the baltic republics and 
the formation of scouting groups elsewhere is considered likely 
poland an active scouting program existed before world war ii 
in postwar years the movement dropped out of the world 
organization but an initiative began in march to qualify for 
readmission through policy reforms 
east germany romania and bulgaria scouting movements in these 
countries were persecuted systematically by the nazis and their 
allies in the 1930s and never were reestablished fully east 
germanys program is expected to merge with west germanys after 
unification but in bulgaria and romania the world scout bureau 
said there are still great difficulties to overcome 
the bureau is the central office for the world organization of 
the scout movement which represents about 16 million scouts in 150 
countries and territories 
the largest scouting movements are in the united states with 39 
million scouts the philippines and indonesia with about 2 million 
india with 12 million and britain with 681000 
