<TEXT>
iran asked the world court on 
tuesday for punitive damages and compensation from the us 
government for the july 3 1988 downing of an iranian commercial 
jetliner by a us navy missile 
the 300page brief termed a memorial in world court parlance 
apparently set no monetary figures all 290 people aboard the 
airbus were killed 
iran also asked the court to order the united states to refrain 
from violating international law and rebuked the us government 
for its continued naval presence in the persian gulf 
the airbus was hit by a missile from the uss vincennes part 
of a task force in the gulf during the iraniraq war the jet 
bound from bandar abbas to dubai was mistaken as an attacking 
warplane in the closing days of the war 
investigations showed the plane was in a normal climbing pattern 
when hit 
iran also submitted three volumes of exhibits 
it sought compensation for families of the victims of the airbus 
downing for the tehran government and for the airline iran air 
it asked punitive damages for what it called the criminal 
nature of the act 
iran demanded a reparations declaration but did not specify 
in the memorials introduction what that declaration would involve 
elements of the introduction were obtained by the associated 
press 
iran filed the case in may 1989 and the bush administration 
said it would take part in the proceedings washington has until 
march 4 to file its corresponding memorial 
the court the judicial arm of the un has no enforcement 
powers and depends on the voluntary adherence of states coming 
before it 
irans memorial was intended to prove that the court has 
jurisdiction over the case and to state the facts of its claim 
the memorial said america refused to accept responsibility for 
the airbus downing and continued to provoke iran by its naval 
presence in the gulf 
it also wants the council of the international civil aviation 
organization to reverse a november 1988 refusal to condemn 
washington for the incident 
iran said the united states violated iranian sovereignty as well 
as un charter provisions barring the use of force and assuring 
freedom of navigation 
besides iranians the plane carried passengers from india 
italy kuwait pakistan yugoslavia and united arab emirates 
thenpresident reagan announced an offer of compensation to 
victims families eight days after the incident 
the compensation process for noniranian victims began in 1989 
250000 to the families of wageearners 100000 to the families 
of other victims 
iran insisted on being compensated directly for the downing and 
refused to provide a list of eligible next of kin 
irans compensation demands include for life lost mental 
suffering the loss of the plane itself and the cost of search and 
rescue operations 
the world court case is likely to be handled by the us and 
iranian officials representing their governments at the iranunited 
states claims tribunal in the hague 
