<TEXT>
a major television network claimed new allies 
tuesday in the networks fight to change tv syndication rules while 
a motion picture industry leader accused nbc cbs and nbc of trying 
to stifle competition 
nbc told the federal communications commission that the 
millionmember national education association and the advocacy 
group action for childrens television no longer support the 
existing syndication rules and that several other groups support 
the network position 
at issue is whether the three major networks should be given the 
right to invest in shows they air and then reap the benefits of 
both foreign and domestic syndication or redistribution as movies 
or videotapes 
an fcc rule in effect since 1970 bars the networks from having a 
financial interest in shows they dont wholly own and bars them 
from syndicating even their own shows in the united states 
opponents say the financial interest and syndication rule 
discourages the major networks from taking risks to develop 
innovative programs proponents of the rule say it prevents the 
networks from dominating primetime television 
the movie industry and the major networks failed to resolve the 
issue after several years of negotiations and the fcc has said it 
will decide whether to rescind the rules after taking final 
comments aug 1 
nbc in a statement filed with the commission said groups with 
a combined membership of about 20 million people support a repeal 
of the rule they include hundreds of local television stations 
labor unions teachers organizations and senior citizen and other 
consumer groups the network said 
most do not have any economic stake in the outcome of this 
rulemaking proceeding but recognize the value of maintaining a 
free and diverse television program service nbc said in its 
statement signed by general counsel richard cotton 
in an interview cotton said the industry has changed 
considerably since the 1970s when the three major networks 
commanded 90 percent of the primetime audience a recent survey 
showed audiences for nbc abc and cbs totalling 52 percent he said 
he said 60 percent of us homes now have cable television with 
an average of 30 stations per household compared to seven in 1970s 
he said networks purchase only 21 percent of programs compared with 
75 percent in 1970 
the network was responding to an assertion by jack valenti 
president of the motion picture association of america that only 
the networks support repeal of the rule 
valenti said in a speech tuesday the public would be illserved 
when a few people accumulate lifeanddeath authority over what 
americans see on primetime television 
he said the rules serves as a check on network abuse of power 
the rule valenti said has restored competition to a program 
arena previously barren to competition and it has allowed 
independent television stations to grow and prosper 
