<TEXT>
oileating bacteria are breaking down 
the mess left by the exxon valdez spill in prince william sound and 
should be used on other spills the nations top environmental 
official said 
william k reilly chief of the environmental protection agency 
said monday that such bioremediation efforts should continue on 
shores fouled by the exxon valdez spill even if that means a third 
summer of cleanup 
state and coast guard officials disagree over how long manual 
and mechanical methods like flushing and tilling should accompany 
bioremediation in the bioremediation method used here chemical 
fertilizers that promote the growth of oileating bacteria were 
spread on sullied beaches 
theres no question that we have made progress toward cleanup 
that is notable significant and very encouraging reilly told 
reporters after his shoreline tour with alaska environmental 
commissioner dennis kelso 
it was reillys first visit to prince william sound since late 
last summer and his third since the tanker exxon valdez ran 
aground in march 1989 spewing nearly 11 million gallons of crude 
oil in the nations biggest oil spill 
the success of bioremediation here bodes well for other oil 
spills and for sites nationwide that have been polluted by leaking 
underground storage tanks reilly said 
i would very much hope that bioremediation comes on in a big 
way throughout the united states reilly said we are 
developing an intimate familiarity with oil spills and we 
desperately need new technologies 
some environmentalists opposed spreading the phosphorous and 
nitrogenbased fertilizers on the shoreline fearing they might 
wreak havoc on an environment already battered by the massive spill 
however no major adverse effects have been reported since the 
fertilizers were spread earlier this summer officials said 
in june natural oileating microbes were used to clean up a 
light crude oil spill off galveston texas the successful effort 
marked the first time bioremediation was used in open waters 
meanwhile state and coast guard officials are arguing about how 
long the cleanup should continue in alaska and who is authorized to 
end it 
kelso has said work should continue anywhere there are more than 
