<DOCNO> AP900724-0181 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a study casts new doubt on federal reports that 
list hospital death rates and fuels concern that the reports are a 
poor measure of hospital quality a researcher said tuesday 
researchers for the rand corp found that varying death rates 
among two types of heart patients could be attributed to random 
statistical variations rather than the treatment the patients 
received 
their report is published in wednesdays journal of the american 
medical association it follows by six months a study published in 
the same journal that criticized the government for inadequately 
examining how the severity of illness may affect hospital death 
rates 
the new study didnt test the most recent method used by the 
health care financing administration to compare mortality rates 
among medicare patients at the nations nearly 6000 hospitals 
but the rand study still urges caution in analyzing the yearly 
reports by the health care administration which adminsters the 
medicare program said rolla edward park principal author 
i think what it points toward is the need to continue to try 
to improve the hcfa methods to figure out what kind of information 
can be put into consumers hands that is the most useful park 
said 
officials at the hcfa which funded part of the rand study said 
they would consider the study in a continuing effort to improve 
their reporting but they said the rand approach to death rates is 
not comparable to theirs 
reports titled medicare hospital mortality information have 
been issued publicly for the past three years by the hcfa an arm 
of the department of health and human services the reports use 
statistical techniques to compare predicted hospital mortality 
rates with the actual number of deaths 
federal officials each year have warned against using the 
reports as the sole measure of a hospitals quality 
rands fourstate study looked at a sample of 2276 deaths among 
medicare patients at 734 hospitals congestive heart failure in 
which the hearts gradual loss of strength causes the lungs to fill 
with fluid accounted for 1126 deaths and heart attacks accounted 
for 1150 
when analyzing the quality of care researchers found some 
hospitals with higherthanexpected death rates called 
targeted hospitals actually provided better care than 
nontargeted hospitals 
researchers found that targeted hospitals treated more serious 
heart attack cases and therefore could reasonably expect higher 
death rates 
no statistical difference was found in the severity of illness 
among patients with congestive heart failure the researchers said 
the researchers used a computer model to measure how much of the 
difference in death rates could be attributed to random variations 
the figures from the simulation roughly matched the actual 
difference in death rates between the targeted and nontargeted 
hospitals the researchers said 
the rand corp is a private nonprofit organization researches 
and analyzes us security and domestic policy 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

