<TEXT>
a proposed 180 million budget for the 
embattled national endowment for the arts including a 900000 
increase in federal funds for state arts agencies was approved 
tuesday by a house appropriations subcommittee 
the bill was sent to the full house appropriations committee by 
voice vote without action on any antiobscenity amendments that 
would restrict the kinds of art eligible for taxpaid endowment 
grants 
a major house floor fight had been expected to begin friday on 
separate legislation that would extend the neas life for another 
five years but late in the day tuesday jeff biggs press aide to 
speaker thomas s foley dwash said that debate had been 
postponed until after the august recess because more than 20 
amendments needed to be considered 
republicans are drafting proposals for a drastic overhaul of the 
endowment as a result of past financial support for art that 
conservatives have denounced as obscene or sacrilegious 
the appropriations bill approved by the subcommittee tuesday 
would provide a 5 percent increase in the nea budget from 1713 
million to 180 million in the fiscal year that begins oct 1 
at the urging of rep sidney yates dill the subcommittee 
chairman and a staunch arts advocate the panel approved boosting 
endowment funds for states arts councils from 261 million to 27 
million 
increases for dance music opera and musical theater the media 
arts and design arts also were approved 
a major proposal of the house republican plan to restructure the 
arts endowment would funnel 60 percent of nea grant money to the 
states compared with the current level of 20 percent 
the gop measure drafted chiefly by reps tom coleman of 
missouri and steve gunderson of wisconsin also would require the 
nea chairman to assure congress that federally supported art is 
sensitive to the nature of public sponsorship and to the cultural 
heritage of the united states its religious traditions or racial 
or ethnic groups and does not violate prevailing standards of 
obscenity 
the obscenity provision is the most controversial feature of the 
colemangunderson plan which will be submitted when the house 
begins debate on the neas reauthorization bill later this week 
the endowment is an independent federal agency that underwrites 
a wide variety of artists and arts institutions with taxpaid 
grants requiring matching funds from private sources 
for more than a year the nea has been the focus of a growing 
political controversy over its previous support for exhibitions of 
sexually explicit works by the late photographer robert 
mapplethorpe and artist andres serrano 
under pressure from sen jesse helms rnc and other 
conservative legislators and from religious fundamentalists 
congress voted last fall to prohibit the nea from supporting 
artwork that may be considered obscene including depictions of 
sex acts sadomasochism homoeroticism or sexual exploitation of 
children 
the colemangunderson antiobscenity provision is based on the 
supreme courts 1973 definition of obscenity which covers works 
that appeal to prurient interest portray patently offensive sexual 
conduct and lack serious artistic scientific political or 
literary value based on community standards 
the republican bill would allow the endowment to recover grant 
funds if the nea chairman concluded that a recipients work 
violated the supreme court standards on obscenity the recipient 
could appeal in federal court 
</TEXT>
