<TEXT>
sixteen people were charged tuesday with 
participating in a scheme to rob homes and businesses of jewelry 
rare coins and precious gems and then resell the merchandise in 
manhattans diamond district 
two men who owned several businesses in the district were 
identified as the leaders of the fencing ring which authorities 
said was in operation since 1982 
james m fox assistant director of the fbis new york office 
said the participants would use every opportunity to commit a 
robbery 
some were blatant armed robberies in broad daylight on the 
streets of manhattan other times they cased out residences or 
businesses and would go in covertly fox said at a news 
conference with us attorney otto obermaier 
fox said it was not uncommon for jewelry to be reset and 
displayed in one of the ringleaders stores as quickly as two hours 
after it was stolen 
although court papers said the defendants netted 12 million 
fox said the amount could be much higher because the scheme had 
been going on for so long 
court papers listed a series of robberies of homes and 
businesses in new jersey from 1983 to 1985 the theft of 221000 
worth of jewelry from a greek exporting company in 1987 and 10 
rolex watches from a foreign shipment in 1986 and the armed 
robbery of a north palm beach fla home in 1983 that netted 
60000 worth of jewelry and merchandise 
fox and obermaier released three separate indictments arising 
from the fencing scheme one charged the two store owners felix 
friedman and lawrence tinnirello and seven others with 
racketeering and various fraud counts 
friedman and tinnirello operated as many as 13 stores some of 
which are still in business in the diamond district located on 
47th street between fifth and sixth avenues authorities said 
the racketeering indictment also outlined a scheme in which the 
defendants allegedly obtained jewelry from other merchants on 
consignment and then kept the items without paying the owner 
friedman who was described by a prosecutor as the business 
brains behind the fence people was ordered held without bail by 
us magistrate naomi buchwald she found he was likely to threaten 
witnesses if released 
tinnirello was held overnight pending a further bail hearing 
wednesday assistant us attorney james comey said both had been 
involved in acts of violence 
four other men were charged with robbery conspiracy in 
connection with the robbery of a brooklyn jewelry store last year 
and a fifth was accused of fraud in the consignment scheme 
a third indictment charged the wives of the store owners irina 
zaritskaya and mindy tinnirello with making false statements to 
banks in order to hide the profits of the fencing scheme they each 
face up to five years in prison on one count of making false 
statements to banks they were released on their own recognizance 
