keystone camera products corp claiming to be 
the last american maker of conventional fixedfocus cameras lost 
its bid tuesday for trade relief from imports 
the four us international trade commission members voted 
unanimously against granting the import quotas and higher tariffs 
the clifton nj firm sought 
imports of cameras were not a substantial cause of injury to 
the domestic camera industry the commission members found 
keystone which made 25 million cameras last year claims it is 
the sole remaining american manufacturer of conventional 35mm fixed 
focus and pointandshoot cameras and pocket cameras in the popular 
110 film size 
its petition excluded imported disc singlelens reflex instant 
print and 110 cameras with variable focus 
keystone contended that imports from japan china taiwan hong 
kong mexico south korea thailand and brazil have hurt the 
domestic camera industry and could jeopardize the future of 500 
manufacturing and distribution jobs 
the company said that imports of the types of cameras it 
produces increased from 11 million in 1985 to 275 million in 1987 
earlier chairman myron j berman had said that without import 
restrictions keystone would be forced to move production overseas 
as other camera makers have done he said keystone already had cut 
costs to the bone 
keystone could pursue alternate appeals for help such as 
charging that foreign cameras have been dumped in the american 
marketplace at less than fairmarket value said betsy godley a 
spokesman for the trade panel 
photography giant eastman kodak co of rochester ny which 
said it was not being hurt by imports had asked the trade 
commission to deny relief to keystone 
kodak which operates around the world argued that keystone was 
responsible for its own market troubles because of poor management 
decisions 
kodak also had disputed keystones claim to be the last bona 
fide american camera maker 
