<TEXT>
gov mario cuomo signed legislation tuesday 
to give new yorkers the power to designate someone to make 
lifeanddeath medical decisions for them when they are no longer 
able to 
cuomos action makes new york the first state to change its laws 
regarding living wills since the us supreme court last month 
ruled that the constitution guarantees a person the right to refuse 
medical treatment 
new york was one of just nine states that lacked such a law 
the choices posed by medical advances will still be difficult 
but the added anguish of legal uncertainty and confusion will 
be removed for patients who have created a health care proxy 
cuomo said 
the bill effective in six months allows new yorkers to 
designate a friend or relative to make health care decisions for 
them such as when lifesupport systems should be unplugged the 
proxy must be signed in front of two witnesses and two doctors must 
certify a patient is no longer able to make such decisions before 
the proxy can be used 
proxy forms will be distributed in such places as hospitals 
nursing homes and doctors offices said tracy miller executive 
director of the state task force on life and the law the health 
department is also printing a brochure that will explain the new 
rights to people she said 
the legislation was passed a week after the supreme court in a 
decision involving a missouri woman named nancy cruzan gave a 
boost to living will legislation new york states highest 
court has said a competent adult has the right to refuse medical 
treatment even if it is lifesustaining 
</TEXT>
