<TEXT>
for 80yearold hilda berikoff the 
reparations she received this year for her world war ii evacuation 
and internment meant the end of one bureaucratic battle and the 
beginning of another 
legally reparations should have no effect on public assistance 
but bureaucratic and communication snags are costing berikoff and 
some other elderly aleuts their medicaid coupons and oldage 
benefits 
berikoff said she hasnt gotten that aid for a couple of months 
i was getting it all the time before she said but then when 
they found out i had money in the bank i think i stopped getting 
it 
at least three people in this aleutian island village have had 
their assistance suspended or canceled by the state division of 
public assistance said marti norton a fee agent who helps people 
correspond with the agency 
a lot of these elderly people arent familiar with paperwork 
and theyre being required to provide more and more information 
said norton one person even had his case closed 
the number of aleuts denied aid in smaller villages without fee 
agents may be much higher 
aleuts on the aleutian and pribilof islands were evacuated on 24 
hours notice after the japanese bombed unalaska in 1942 berikoff 
said she still can close her eyes and hear bombs dropping and feel 
the fear and panic 
the aleuts were taken to camps in southeast alaska for 2 
years the berikoffs lived in a defunct cannery and bunkhouse on 
burnett island four families shared a room with one large table 
many slept on the table others on the floor berikoff stuffed 
blankets under the doors to keep out the cold 
they said theyd have everything for us ready in southeast and 
when we got there there was nothing she said i had two little 
kids so it was pretty hard on me 
many aleuts returned after the war to find their homes and 
belongings missing or destroyed and the russian orthodox church 
vandalized for years they sought reparations berikoff was among 
those who lobbied congress 
in 1988 congress approved reparations of 12000 per person to 
be distributed by the bureau of indian affairs 
berikoff has arthritis doing without medicaid coupons and 136 
in oldage benefits each month means she has little money left 
after paying bills she said she has spent most of her reparations 
money to fix her house 
i wouldnt be able to go to the clinic unless they pay she 
said 
in berikoffs case the division sent a letter saying it would 
close her file unless she provided a copy of her bank statement 
proof she received reparations and an account of what she did with 
the money norton said 
im really offended that they would burden an 80yearold lady 
with all of this said norton this payment was supposed to 
make up for wrongs it was supposed to make their lives a little 
easier 
of some 550 aleuts eligible for reparations all but about 130 
received checks by may said dimitri philemonof executive director 
of the nonprofit native corporation aleutianpribilof islands 
association the rest he said will be paid by next year 
the money should not affect individuals government aid 
reparations are not considered income and are not taxable 
state welfare workers were told this but some were confused and 
in at least one case benefits to an aleut were cut off without 
proper notice said curtis lomas a program officer in juneau 
workers will receive new materials to reiterate the rules he 
said 
the state must make sure that the 12000 its publicaid clients 
received were reparations lomas said if the division doesnt get 
the right documents it sends letters giving clients 10 to 15 days 
to respond 
if its not provided after a reasonable period of time we 
have no choice but to close the case he said there are people 
who just dont respond 
norton said some older aleuts who receive packets in the mail 
dont open them immediately 
many of them are intimidated when you get a big fat envelope 
in the mail she said a lot of them would put it on a dresser 
for awhile and look at it because they were sure it was bad news 
then theyd bring it to me and a lot of times it was too late 
state aid forms are dense and hard to read even for people whose 
first language is english norton said many elderly aleuts speak 
little or no english 
lomas says welfare officials do the best we can we dont have 
the capability of issuing notices in aleut 
reparations have created other problems i think there are 
some carpetbaggers out there ready to pounce on people with new 
wealth philemonof said all of a sudden youve got friends 
norton tells of one man who bought a goldnugget watch and ring 
and drank away the rest of his settlement in a month then he had 
to sell the jewelry 
one of the biggest problems people have run into philemonof 
said is cashing checks in smaller villages theres not enough 
revenue there and they were more or less forced to come into 
anchorage he said 
