<TEXT>
a tragedy vast in scope is unfolding on the arid 
plains of central asia a region already unsettled by stirrings of 
dissent and nationalism this is the third article in a fourpart 
series based on an ap special correspondents journey through the 
soviet south 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
beyond bukharas irrigated deserts the 
noble amu darya river dwindles down to a pathetic poisonous 
trickle a victim in one of the worlds worst ecological disasters 
deprived of the amu darya and its sister stream the syr darya 
the aral sea is dying within 30 years what was the worlds fourth 
largest inland sea is expected to be only a dry bed of deadly salt 
scientists say the seas condition reflects a far greater crisis 
across much of central asia caused by years of soviet insistence 
on defying nature to plant cotton in the desert 
near the aral the effects are devastating authorities refused 
entry to a western reporter seeking to verify reports of the 
highest infant mortality rates in the world 
but videotape made in june by a soviet filmmaker showed 
ecological refugees in squalid camps a hospital full of children 
poisoned by their mothers milk and whole communities disappearing 
in some places doctors said on film 63 percent of the children 
are sick with lung or kidney disorders damaged livers rickets 
pneumonia anemia or other diseases sickness comes from pesticides 
and defoliants inhaled with blowing salt or swallowed with tainted 
water mothers pass on chemicals to nursing infants 
the physical setting has suffered as dramatically 
rusting hulks sit stranded on a vast desert once a seabed the 
remains of one of the soviet unions richest inland fishing fleets 
no fish has been caught in the aral since 1977 
the filmmaker andrei yatsenia was among specialists who met in 
tashkent late in may to focus attention on what they agreed was 
the ecological plunder of central asia 
this is catastrophic said permat shermuhamedov a regional 
legislator who heads the committee to save the aral sea at this 
rate the sea is finished 
the experts blamed two problems widespread irrigation by raw 
gashes in the porous earth which wastes as much water as it 
carries and the excessive use of pesticides defoliants and 
corrosive chemicals that pollute the remaining seawater 
since 1960 the aral sea has lost half its surface area the 
equivalent of almost two lake eries each year winds carry 
millions of tons of salt from dried lakebeds tainting fields up to 
a thousand miles away 
close to its former shores the lake is already regarded as a 
mass murderer 
in parts of karakalpakia an autonomous region of uzbekistan 
the official infant mortality rate is 112 per 1000 four times the 
soviet average and higher than in most poor african nations 
but doctors say even that figure is understated 
pediatricians in some pockets say the rate is 500 every 
second child dies in his first year said gulchehra nurullaeva a 
poet and official of birlik an uzbek grassroots opposition party 
doctors link the high rate directly to health problems from the 
dying aral sea 
karakalpak authorities invited a correspondent to investigate 
conditions but the uzbekistan foreign ministry would not grant a 
visa 
what can we do with the land salted and no water asked one 
desperate father on yatsenias tape in a squatter camp of 650 mud 
hovels if the aral dies hundreds and thousands will die with 
it 
in the moribund town of muynak water once lapped at the back 
door of a large cannery now the sea is at least 14 miles away the 
plant still operates frozen fish are brought thousands of miles 
from the ocean 
even here in bukhara 400 miles to the south the crisis is 
evident 
every fall at the edge of this ancient caravan hub the 
madaniyat collective farm picks its cotton crop and bundles it off 
toward moscow and every year the cost is higher 
long ago bukharas zeravshan river exhausted itself before 
reaching the amu darya bled by too many irrigation canals to 
replace it a new canal was cut to drain yet more of the amu darya 
before fields can be planted they must be washed clean of salt 
and excess chemicals which are carried down toward the aral 
a decade ago a grand dream envisioned a 1400mile 
multibilliondollar canal from siberia to the amu darya but that 
would devastate siberian marshes environmentalists showed 
with no alternate sources central asia water users merely 
fought harder for their allotments 
the tragedy is that most of this water is just wasted into 
the desert and into the air said vladimir kovaleyev a geologist 
who has studied the problem for decades 
i shouted in literaturnaya gazeta in 1975 but people were 
deaf he said brandishing clippings from other papers as well 
today they still are not listening 
</TEXT>
