<TEXT>
a senate leader called on the securities and 
exchange commission and the commodity futures trading commission to 
work out their differences after a report faulted both agencies for 
their conflicting analyses of last octobers stock market slide 
a general accounting office report found that differences in the 
sec and cftc studies stemmed from subjective interpretation and 
judgment 
the two rival agencies which have been embroiled in a 
jurisdictional dispute each issued reports last month analyzing 
the oct 13 190point drop in the dow jones industrial average 
both studies differed in their conclusions and both agencies 
later lambasted the others methodology prompting a senate panel 
to request a study of the issue by the gao the investigative arm 
of congress 
sec and cftc emphasize different factors and take different 
points of view to reach their conclusions this sometimes results 
in different conclusions each of which is supported by basically 
the same trading data said the gao report which was released by 
the securities subcommittee of the senate banking committee 
the sec reported that index arbitrage and other program selling 
strategies significantly worsened the market decline while the cftc 
reported that neither program trading nor futures sales explained 
the sharp price movements on the day of and first trading day after 
the drop 
index arbitrage is a computerized program trading strategy that 
seeks to take advantage of small differences between the stock and 
futures markets by simultaneously buying large orders in one market 
while selling in the other 
stock index futures often used in program trading strategies 
allow investors to trade on the movement of a basket of stocks 
without having to buy the underlying stocks 
the gao report finds the seccftc jurisdictional dispute 
continues to detract from their working relationship said sen 
christopher j dodd dconn chairman of the subcommittee 
the agencies major differences threatens their ability to 
work together to minimize risks to the capital markets this 
untenable situation must be resolved he added 
spokesmen for the sec and cftc denied that their feud was 
hurting their ability to work together on other issues 
we dont feel that the ongoing debate has compromised the 
commissions ability to work with its sister agency the sec 
said cftc spokesman david gary that fact has most recently been 
shown by todays market activity he said referring to a more 
than 100point drop in the dow during the early hours of trading 
monday 
our staff people have talked to the exchanges cftc chairman 
wendy gramm has spoken with sec chairman richard breeden and 
when appropriate we have passed along information that was 
necessary for the sec to do its job said gary 
sec officials declined to comment because they had not seen the 
final report but they noted that except for the dispute over stock 
index futures the agencies get along wonderfully 
the bush administration wants to strip the cftc of its authority 
over stock index futures and give it to the sec 
the sec said it stood by written comments on an earlier draft of 
the gao report 
in a letter to the gao richard ketchum the director of the 
secs market regulation division maintained that the secs 
findings are amply supported both by detailed analyses of 
specific trade data and extensive interviews with relevant market 
participants 
ketchums letter then went on to criticize a letter by cftc 
chairman gramm last month that faulted the sec study as 
misleading and contradictory 
in its study the sec concluded that index arbitrage and other 
program trading strategies accelerated the 69 percent market drop 
and accounted for an unusually high percentage of share volume 
during the 90minute slide 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

