<TEXT>
nearly 50 pennsylvania corporations have 
decided to exempt themselves in whole or part from the states 
tough antitakeover law and the list is growing as thursdays 
deadline for acting approaches 
by monday 47 companies had said no to embracing the full law 
and more companies were expected to join the ranks according to 
william a k titelman an attorney who lobbied against the law and 
is now tabulating the companies who are opting out 
among those taking the action are roughly half of the 
pennsylvania companies on the fortune 500 and standard and poors 
500 lists 
the more the pennsylvania business community has gotten to 
know the bill the more they dislike it at least for themselves 
titelman said in a telephone interview 
but bill baer vice president for government affairs for the 
pennsylvania chamber of business and industry which championed the 
law said it was agreed that this was not going to be one size 
fits all and companies were going to decide what was in their 
best interest 
enacted in april the law gave publicly traded companies until 
july 26 to decide privately held companies have a year to make up 
their minds 
the law regarded as the nations toughest against hostile 
takeovers for the first time requires unsuccessful raiders to 
surrender their profits if they sell the stock within 18 months of 
the attempted takeover the clause is aimed at socalled 
greenmailers who target a company they hope will buy back its 
shares at a premium to make the raiders go away 
raiders who gain 20 percent or more of a company will not get 
voting rights until other stockholders approve and company 
directors can balance the interests of stockholders employees and 
others in weighing a takeover bid 
investor groups bitterly fought the bill arguing it would 
depress stock values but proponents said it was vital to stopping 
profithungry financiers from gobbling up pennsylvania companies 
breaking them up and destroying jobs and communities 
impetus for the law came from lawmakers intent on saving 
armstrong world industries of lancaster from a takeover bid by the 
belzberg family of canada the belzbergs have since abandoned their 
plans titelman a partner in the klett lieber rooney amp schorling 
law firm of pittsburgh represented the belzbergs 
state sen noah wenger rlancaster who sponsored the law said 
he hoped companies werent being lulled by the slowdown in hostile 
takeovers and would remember that takeovers could start anew if 
financing again became available some may feel the protections 
are not as needed as they were a few years ago wenger said 
that may be deceptive 
william george president of the aflcio which succeeded in 
adding job protection sections to the law said investors have 
pressured some companies into exempting themselves he also noted 
that some companies that were presented as needing protection have 
since exempted themselves 
when lawmakers were considering the bill proponents said 
conrail was an example of a pennsylvania company that needed 
protection and the argument swayed votes to the bill 
but july 18 conrails board announced it was exempting itself 
from the sections stripping raiders profits also known as 
disgorgement and blocking immediate voting rights for a raider 
known as control shares 
company spokesman david neurohr said conrail felt initially that 
the bill moving through the legislature was a mixed bag 
although the company supported it but once optional features were 
added and remained in the law the conrail board felt compelled to 
choose those that are in the best interest of the company 
employees and community neurohr said 
among the top companies opting out of all sections of the new 
law are hj heinz co pnc financial corp westinghouse electric 
corp and the reading co 
companies opting out of disgorgement and control shares include 
allegheny ludlum corp dravo corp duquesne light co kennametal 
inc and mellon bank 
the sun co has opted out of disgorgement 
despite the decision of its board to push for the law the 
chamber of business and industry was by no means unanimous on 
accepting all its provisions 
richard ross jr the chambers chairman announced monday that 
his company first eastern corp had opted out of the disgorgement 
and control shares sections of the laws 
</TEXT>
