<TEXT>
the house has passed legislation giving the 
securities and exchange commission new powers to impose fines for 
illegal activities beyond insider trading less than a week earlier 
a similar bill cleared the senate 
the house also passed legislation that would crack down on penny 
stock fraud 
the penny stock bill which combined two earlier bills cleared 
through committee last month was passed on a voice vote by the 
house monday 
the securities enforcement and penny stock reform act of 1990 
also would give the sec authority to order alleged wrongdoers to 
cease and desist illegal activities without first having to go 
to court and obtain a restraining order 
the legislation would widen sec authority to seek court orders 
barring convicted securities law violators from serving as officers 
or directors of companies with publicly traded stock 
the senate passed a bill last week giving the sec similar 
authority to fine issue cease and desist orders and ask courts to 
bar crooks from serving as corporate officers 
a separate penny stock bill also is pending in the senate 
the penny stock provisions of the house bill would give the sec 
the power to bar crooked promoters and consultants from selling the 
highly speculative stocks which usually sell for 1 or less 
penny stocks are not traded on most stock exchanges the bulk of 
the information obtainable about them comes from the brokers sho 
sell them while not illegal penny stocks which typically are 
used to finance new or small companies are considered to be very 
risky at best 
the house bill would allow the sec 
to close a loophole that now allows unscrupulous penny stock 
brokers to evade sec removal from the securities business by 
calling themselves promoters or consultants which the sec has no 
power to regulate 
to tighten disclosure requirements for highly speculative 
investments known as blind pools and blank checks 
in their combined form these two bills represent a powerful 
expansion of the enforcement weapons available to combat the 
problems of securities fraud in general and the penny stock market 
in particular said rep edward j markey dmass who sponsored 
the initial penny stock legislation along with reps matthew 
rinaldo rnj and ron wyden dore 
the other half of the bill originally was introduced by rep 
john dingell dmich chairman of the house energy and commerce 
committee which oversees the sec 
