<TEXT>
the 1990 farm bill sent to the senate by its 
agriculture committee is surviving major changes 
the senate was debating an amendment today that would reduce 
guarantees to sugar producers from 18 cents a pound to 16 cents 
the house meanwhile faced more than 100 amendments in taking 
up its version of the bill today 
on monday the senate defeated an amendment that would have made 
significant changes in the section on sustainable agriculture 
that system of farming the seeks reduction in chemical use 
the proposal offered by sen charles grassley riowa would 
have weakened a provision was meant to enhance government 
activities to encourage sustainable agriculture it was defeated 
6032 
the senate defeated 6229 an amendment by sen harry reid 
dnev to discontinue use of animals for acute toxicity testing in 
product safety experiments 
opponents said the measure said it was a commerce committee 
problem that should make its way to the floor through that panel 
not as an addition to the farm bill 
the senate approved amendments that would 
authorize 250000 to study the effects of timber harvesting 
and deforestation in the new york and new jersey highlands 
make wood products eligible for agricultural export programs 
require that the agriculture department phase in changes in 
research programs so that by 1993 the agricultural research 
service is spending 20 percent of its budget on alternative crops 
and products the bill authorizes 730 million annually for the 
service during the fiveyear life of the bill 
sen tom daschle dsd criticized the agriculture department 
as oriented too much toward increasing crop yields 
we produce so much we dont know what to do with it sen 
john glenn dohio said in support of the amendment this says 
we want to channel some of this research into nonfood uses 
products that are under development now include using corn as a 
substitute for road salt soybean oil as a pesticide carrier and 
corn and wheat starches to make products biodegradable 
