<TEXT>
aerospace manufacturer mcdonnell douglas 
corp is defending itself against a 6 million lawsuit filed by 
lloyds of london alleging negligence for damage to a satellite 
the case stems from a june 20 1989 accident at a cape 
canaveral launch pad in which a 65pound crane hook crashed into an 
80 million communications satellite on a delta rocket 
the satellite was insured by lloyds and the manufacturer 
repaired it at an estimated cost of 10 million the insurance 
group wants to recover part og the costs 
the suit alleges that mcdonnell and employees of its space 
operations unit negligently and carelessly planned simulated 
trained for and conducted the handling and removal procedure in a 
way that caused the crane cable to snap while loading the satellite 
it accuses mcdonnell employees of reckless wanton and gross 
negligence in violating statutes and industry standards for 
operation of an overhead crane 
the suit was filed last month in brevard county circuit court 
and mcdonnell has petitioned for its transfer to federal court 
because the accident occurred on us government property 
the case is the second in the commercial space launch industry 
in a month 
martin marietta corp and the international telecommunications 
satellite oraganization went to court earlier this month to decide 
who should pay for a satellite launch failure in march 
a martin mariettabuilt titan 4 rocket failed to boost the 157 
million intelsat satellite into the proper orbit 
</TEXT>
