<TEXT>
opec ministers tuesday began gathering for a 
critical strategy session that has been overshadowed by iraqi 
threats to punish cartel members that exceed their oil production 
limits 
the meeting is taking place as oil prices continue a rebound 
from lows of earlier this year that served to aggravate the 
political tensions raised by iraq especially against neighboring 
cartel member kuwait 
a number of ministers expressed support for increasing the 
cartels benchmark price for its crude from the current 18 a 
barrel which would require agreement on new production limits 
but ministers of the organization of petroleum exporting 
countries sidestepped the confrontation between iraq and kuwait 
we are here to solve oil problems said saudi arabias 
influential oil minister hisham nazer as he arrived for the 
midyear meeting scheduled for thursday 
iraqs oil minister issam abdul raheem alchalabi was 
surrounded by dozens of reporters as he entered the lobby of a 
luxury hotel where the talks are held he only discussed his plans 
to press for an increase in the current 18 a barrel benchmark 
price for the cartels crude oil 
the cartels discussions have taken on added significance since 
iraqi president saddam hussein last week threatened to use force 
against countries that exceed their opecset production quotas 
his remarks were aimed at kuwait and the united arab emirates 
two gulf producers that have violated their output ceilings 
saddam claimed his debtridden country has lost 14 billion 
during the past year because of a world oil glut that sent crude 
prices tumbling iraq also has charged that kuwait stole 24 
billion worth of iraqi oil since 1980 from wells it dug on iraqi 
territory across their common border 
iraq reportedly has moved 30000 troops to its border with 
kuwait and battlefield missiles armored personnel carriers and 
tanks were displayed prominently along the road from iraq to kuwait 
the united states on tuesday expressed concern with the buildup 
and confirmed its naval forces were holding a joint exercise in the 
persian gulf with the united arab emirates 
the iraqi threats were made a week after saudi arabia and four 
other gulf producers proposed an accord designed to halt the 
runaway production of kuwait and the united arab emirates 
nazer told reporters he was confident opec would reach an 
agreement along the lines of the gulf proposal that plan would 
limit the cartels production to about 225 million barrels a day 
in the next few months 
the cartels cap for the first half of the year was 221 million 
barrels however a confidential report prepared by opecs 
secretariat in vienna put actual production at 235 million barrels 
a day in the apriljune quarter according to sources familiar with 
the document 
demand for the cartels oil was estimated at 218 million 
barrels a day in the third quarter of this year rising to 244 
million barrels in the last three months of the year said the 
sources who demanded anonymity 
the opec market report said an overall production ceiling of 22 
million barrels a day in the second half of the year would improve 
prices considerably 
opecs excess production sent prices tumbling in the spring 
the average price of a basket of seven crudes monitored by the 
cartel plummeted to 1364 a barrel in june before climbing to 
1625 a barrel last week 
the september contract for the benchmark us crude finished at 
2056 a barrel late tuesday on the new york mercantile exchange 
up 6 cents from monday and up about 5 from its lows in june 
iran has proposed a reference price of 20 a barrel while iraq 
wants a 25 level nazer said saudi arabia supported a price hike 
but he did not mention a figure 
iraqs chalabi said his country was aiming for 25 and gabons 
jean ping said he would like to see the target raised above 18 
under the gulf proposal kuwait and the united arab emirates 
each would limit output to 15 million barrels a day the two 
separately have been pumping as much as 2 million barrels a day 
kuwaits current production cap is 15 million barrels a day 
and the uae quota is 11 million barrels 
while the cartels official summer meeting opens thursday its 
eightmember monitoring panel will hold talks wednesday 
opec members are algeria ecuador gabon indonesia iran 
iraq kuwait libya nigeria qatar saudi arabia the united arab 
emirates and venezuela 
</TEXT>
