<DOCNO> AP900724-0255 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
mcdonalds corp and wendys international announced monday they 
are switching to cholesterolfree allvegetable oil to cook their 
french fries 
in april anticholesterol crusader phil sokolof placed ads in 
newspapers criticizing mcdonalds and other restaurants for cooking 
fries in beef tallow rather than using hearthealthy oils 
here is a brief explanation of fats 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
all dietary fats are mixtures of three kinds of fatty acids 
saturated monosaturated and polyunsaturated 
according to some studies the relative health merits of 
different oils and fats are determined by the proportions of each 
of the three different kinds of fatty acids in the individual oil 
or fat 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
fats with a higher proportion of saturated fatty acids are 
generally solid at room temperature research indicates they 
increase blood cholesterol 
animal fats have a higher proportion of saturated fatty acids 
than most fats from plants animal fats also contain cholesterol 
tropical oils are derived from plants and therefore contain no 
cholesterol however they are high in saturated fatty acids some 
tropical oils such as palm oil coconut oil and palm kernel oil 
actually have more saturated fatty acids than the animal fats 
hydrogenated fats are other fats of plant origin that have been 
processed or hydrogenated and have become saturated fats the 
degree of saturation is dependent on the processing but generally 
the harder the product is at room temperature the more saturated 
it is examples of hydrogenated products are hard shortenings hard 
or stick margarines and some kinds of peanut butter 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
fats with a high proportion of monosaturated fatty acids do not 
increase blood cholesterol studies suggest the monosaturates 
particularly olive oil actually reduce blood cholesterol levels 
monosaturated fats include olive oil peanut oil and avocado oil 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
fats with a high proportion of polyunsaturated fatty acids are 
found primarily in plants and in some kinds of fish 
polyunsaturates reduce the risk of heart disease by lowering 
cholesterol levels in the blood polyunsaturates include sunflower 
oil corn oil soybean oil cottonseed oil safflower oil and some 
fish oils 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

