<TEXT>
administration officials said tuesday they had 
scrapped the idea of turning over the troubled portfolio of the 
nations largest guarantor of college student loans to a much 
smaller nebraska program 
the officials said the department of education is exploring 
other options including the possibility of finding another agency 
to take over the strained higher education assistance foundation 
the foundation informed the government it is having serious 
problems meeting its obligations to insure nearly 300 million in 
defaulted student loans for fiscal year 1990 
the foundations troubles have raised doubts that it can ensure 
the availability of new loans service its outstanding debt and pay 
on default claims 
were looking at a range of alternatives whereby another 
entity or entities insure all of those functions either on a 
shortor longterm basis said education undersecretary ted 
stevens 
under the scenario that im talking about here heaf would not 
exist he added during a press briefing 
were trying to get to a point of a friendly takeover by a 
stronger guarantor said an official from the office of 
management and budget who requested anonymity 
in a written statement heaf said it was pursuing on its own 
additional options that would enable us to restore confidence to 
its loan guarantees as the peak activity season begins 
however the foundation said it is best that we not speculate 
on how these problems might be resolved or who might be involved 
the omb official identified the united students aids funds in 
indianapolis ind as one possible candidate to take over heaf 
but a proposed merger agreement that would have transferred many 
of heafs loan default obligations to the nebraska student loan 
program inc apparently has been abandoned 
the department determined that the nebraska program would have 
been unable to manage a portfolio the size of heafs it also said 
such a merger would offer only a shortterm remedy and might have 
circumvented the law 
heaf was the nations largest guarantor of student loans last 
year with 96 billion in loans outstanding the outstanding loan 
program of the nebraska program is just under 500 million 
under the merger agreement the federal government would have 
footed the bill for heafs fiscal year 1990 default obligations and 
the foundation would have been allowed to start anew on oct 1 the 
beginning of the 1991 fiscal year 
through the governments guaranteed student loan program 55 
guarantors including heaf insure 100 percent of student loans to 
banks or secondary lenders 
the education department reinsures the loans and reimburses the 
guarantor agency for payments to lenders the reimbursement rates 
begin at 100 percent but drop to 90 percent when reinsurance 
payments exceed five percent when the payments reach 9 percent the 
rate falls to 80 percent 
heaf is the only guarantor to reach the 9 percent level 
dropping the governments repayment rate to 80 percent in april 
heaf has guaranteed billions in trade school loans with high 
default rates such loans accounted for 59 percent of heafs 1988 
portfolio but only 35 percent in 1989 
officials also sought to assure students lenders and other 
agencies that heafs problems do not signal systemwide problems 
for the student loan program 
this situation will not affect the ability of students to 
obtain loans of lenders to make those loans or of guarantors to 
insure those loans education secretary lauro cavazos said 
officials said heafs problems are serious but are isolated to 
that organization 
however education officials said the government is not 
obligated to pay lenders in event of insurance defaults by heaf or 
other guarantors in the event of student loan defaults 
the omb official dismissed temptations to compare problems in 
the student loan program with the multibillion dollar savings and 
loan crisis 
this is not a big federal bailout this is not a federal 
bailout period he said the numbers are big but it is not an 
sampltype situation 
a ninemember education department review team and two 
highranking omb officials were sent monday to heaf offices in st 
paul minn 
</TEXT>
